She went to a blank page and wrote the date. Below it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The King of Ice never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which otherwise consisted only of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had spoken of her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had also changed. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
He also had to remain in service to the princess, but it wasn't too bad, because it gave him a friend.
"I'm sure it's almost your birthday," said Ivory, recalling that the princess's birthday was coming up in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad gleam in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As she asked the question, she remembered what she had told him the last time.
No, Kari hit the mark. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but she remembered the outrage of the servants and the townspeople. She had heard it said that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Bon... what do you feel like doing?" asked he. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed him a piece of paper. But when he glanced at it...
Paint roller screen 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"I do you want me to find these things for you?" Ivory asked, turning toward the silent princess who was typing furiously, shaking her braids back and forth. "Yes?" Iel chuckled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess become so passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" offered Ivory as she stood up and made her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and once again immersed herself in her memories, curling up in her thick comforter.
She exited the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that were not within her realm, such as painting.
She turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"I heard that she was possessed by Queen Eirwen, which is why she always goes to that room."
"I heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
He covered his ears, because trying to ignore them wasn't working. He headed toward the royal painter's room, which was located in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately wrought as Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. There were paint stains everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around the room, easels covering every last centimeter of the wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of this. The room was clean, and there was a red velvet background with a stool right in front. On the stool sat Prince Aquilo, having his portrait painted.
"Oh hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" asked Aquilo to Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Pardon, little prince," he replied, partly ignoring him in order to look for the objects his silent friend desired. "I'm here just to retrieve some supplies."
"Oh, the little girl is going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box that she had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought of it, however. "Oh my darling, you know it's just a phase! It'll pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I have to go," he said, suddenly feeling uneasy, because of the prince's words, which reminded him of all the bad things people had said about his gender identity. I really want to distance myself from him.
"Are you already leaving us?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
"That is not the behavior of a future king!" he rebuked him.
"Nobody will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter will say nothing if he values his life." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you say to a date?" Ivory shivered. Yes, he had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone an heir to the throne.
"Didn't you just now know what the word 'no' means?" he shouted, shoving the prince aside.
"Hé non," said Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go on a date with me instead of with others? You must have a hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling all the time: "Exactly 500." He threw back his hair, letting it fly in the cold air.
"So, why me instead of another? I am the palace's threat." She wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo placed her finger under Ivory's chin and forced her to look at him.
